We first extract the necessary figures from the statements:

1. Net Profit from the income statement: 146,127.58  
2. Total Owner’s Equity from the balance sheet (End_amount): 16,146,127.58  
3. Total Liabilities: Using the balance sheet, the only liabilities shown are Current Liabilities (Accounts Payable + Taxes Payable) which amount to 5,512,978.61  
4. Total Assets from the balance sheet (End_amount): 21,662,106.19  
5. Gross Profit from the income statement: 300,421.65  
6. Total Revenue from the income statement: 863,371.65  

Now we calculate each metric step by step:

A. Return on Equity (ROE)  
  ROE = (Net Profit / Total Owner’s Equity) × 100  
  = (146,127.58 / 16,146,127.58) × 100  
  ≈ 0.00905 × 100  
  ≈ 0.91%

B. Debt to Asset Ratio  
  Debt to Asset Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Assets  
  = 5,512,978.61 / 21,662,106.19  
  ≈ 0.2546  
  ≈ 0.25

C. Gross Profit Margin  
  Gross Profit Margin = (Gross Profit / Total Revenue) × 100  
  = (300,421.65 / 863,371.65) × 100  
  ≈ 0.3482 × 100  
  ≈ 34.82%

Thus, the calculated results are:

{
  "solution": {
    "Return on Equity (ROE)": "0.91%",
    "Debt to Asset Ratio": "0.25",
    "Gross Profit Margin": "34.82%"
  }
}
